President Donald J. Trump has announced his intent to nominate two individuals to key positions in his administration. Christine S. Wilson of Virginia is nominated to be a Member of the Federal Trade Commission. She currently serves as Senior Vice President for Regulatory & International Affairs at Delta Air Lines and has over twenty years of experience as an antitrust and consumer protection practitioner. Before joining Delta, she was a partner at Kirkland & Ellis LLP and served as Chief of Staff to FTC Chairman Timothy J. Muris during the George W. Bush Administration. She has also contributed to the development of competition law and policy through her work in government and private practice. Ms. Wilson received her J.D. from Georgetown University and her B.A. from the University of Florida.

Noah Joshua Phillips of Maryland is nominated to be a Member of the Federal Trade Commission. He currently serves as Chief Counsel to Senator John Cornyn of Texas and has advised the senator on various issues including antitrust, constitutional law, consumer privacy, fraud, and intellectual property. Before his service in the Senate, Mr. Phillips worked as a litigation associate at Cravath, Swaine & Moore LLP and Steptoe & Johnson LLP. He also served as a law clerk for Judge Edward C. Prado of the United States Court of Appeals for the Fifth Circuit. Mr. Phillips began his career at Wasserstein Perella & Co., an investment bank in New York City. He received his A.B. from Dartmouth College and his J.D. from Stanford Law School. Mr. Phillips and his wife, Sarah, have three children.